Infrastructure description

This infrastructure is a distributed web system designed to host www.foobar.com
 using multiple servers and a load balancer to improve performance and scalability.

A user accesses the website through a browser using the domain name www.foobar.com
. DNS resolves the domain name to the load balancer.

A load balancer (HAproxy) distributes incoming traffic between two servers using a Round Robin algorithm, ensuring that requests are evenly distributed across both servers.

The load balancer is configured in an Active-Active setup, meaning both servers are actively handling requests at the same time.

Each server contains a web server (Nginx), an application server, application codebase, and a database system.

The database is configured in a Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) cluster. The Primary database handles write operations, while the Replica database receives replicated data and handles read operations to improve performance.

Load balancer algorithm

The load balancer uses the Round Robin algorithm, where incoming requests are distributed sequentially across available servers in order.

Database role separation

The Primary node is responsible for all write operations, while the Replica node is used for read operations and is synchronized with the Primary.

Issues with this infrastructure
Single Point of Failure: the load balancer is a SPOF, and database failure can impact the system.
Security issues: no firewall and no HTTPS encryption.
No monitoring system is implemented to track performance or failures.
